I held for an hour telling her she'd be ok.  This was her breaking up w/ me.  But oh man have I gotten off track.)  What I wanted to convey is to not be passionate in your breakup unless it's for the other person's good.  Break up with a simple.  "I'm sorry.  This relationship is not working.  It needs to end."  From here on, your job is to easy the breakup on the other person if they desire.  For the girl I told wasn't a priority, later that night I recanted, called back, and let her talk through what she wanted to say to me.  Not because I cared but because it made the breakup easier on her.  And the girl I held for an hour telling her it would be ok.  The very first breakup I had I tried to do it in a place where the girl would have friends she could talk to.  Infact I told a shared friend what I was going to do half an hour ahead of time so that she could comfort my former girlfriend.  What I'm trying to say is be consice at first, but if the other person needs help with the breakup, (I doubt yours will but for future reference), plan ahead and be there to provide it.<br><br>Ok, well, next.  First, guys/gals, either one, many times refuse to see a relationship sliding.  They see the signs but they attribute them to nothing.  PMS, Bad day, etc.  One girlfriend, I could tell she was going to break up w/ me months in advance because when I queezed her hand, she didn't take the time to squeeze it back.  I honestly have never gotten really well to the point in a relationship that it is just stable.  Unchaning and stable rather than incrasing or decreasing in strength over a long period of time.  But I assume it is possible to tell when you have gotten to that point.  And if you are not at it and these things, (not squeezing back, not wanting to spend time together, etc), start happening, the relationship is on a path to die out.<br><br>Next, 3-4 months I think is the minimum for a relationship that starts out good.  If it doesn't last 3-4 months it didn't start out good or there were some obvious character flaws to separate you.  after about 4 months is when I think most relationships have peaked and start to decay to stability. <br><br>Next observation.  It's a HS relationship.  If you haven't dated much before if at all, even if your going into college, it's a highschool relationship.  One where your still figuring out how the game is played.  What the rules are.  The mechanics of the thing.  People should have multiple relationships like this before marrying.  Every relationship lets you look at the beast from a different side.  The more you have the better your vision of the whole idea of a relationship is.  You didn't loose the love of your life.  You'll be ok.  And you will have more relationships that were this good (or this bad) before you find someone you want to live with for the rest of your life.<br><br>And: Archive the evidence.  I still have the very sexually explicit chats I had w/ my girlfriend 2 years ago.  I don't think she'd ever do anything to hurt me, but so help me if she does penthouse is getting some good letters w/ her name attached.<br><br>In conclusion, relationships are good and they are bad.  Remember, it's better to have Loved and lost than to have never Loved at all.  Breaking up with someone is honestly the hardest thing I have ever done.  Whether it was a fling or a long relationship, ending a relationship, especially when the other person doesn't want to, is hard on both sides.  But it is common and what doesn't kill you makes you stronger.<br><br>(On a side note, I am only able to stay friends w/ very few of the girls I have broken up with or who have broken up with me.   If they broke up with me usually it takes me a year to a year and a half to be willing ton consider a friendship again.  No matter who does the breaking up though, it seems alot of girls would like to remain friends, so I think you are probably going to get your friendship.  BTW, the girls that I am still friends with, that I have dated, are probably the friends I trust the most.) <p>--------------------------<br><B><a href=mailto:gyorg@thesafehouse.org>Gyorg Lavode</a></b>, The original <i>Phin-o-matic</i><table><tr><td>   <font color=990033> <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/bthesafehouse.html>Safehouse</a> Moderator</font>   <br><I>Unguilded</i> Rogue Badass    <br>of the <b>58th</b> Moon over Xegony</td><td valign=top>   <img src=http://www.thesafehouse.org/~gyorg/hailgyorg.gif></td></tr></table></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/udragynphyre.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Dragynphyre</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/31/02 12:53:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseranthallgripeswishes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5182.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.mindspring.com/~dragynphyre/images/purpdrag.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Problem</span><hr size=1> Not to derail too badly, but Gyorg, you say 4 months seems to be the turning point in most relationships...Well, if that's the case, think I got a good thing, it'll be 5 months in about a week. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br><br>Kambic, Gyorg brings up a couple good points:  <br><br>1- Take the time to break up in person if at all possible.  Harder at the time, yes, but gives more of a sense of closure...for both of you, which makes it easier to move on.<br><br>2- Have multiple relationships before marrying.<br>How do you know that that guy/gal is the RIGHT one if you haven't had any/many experiences with other people before you settle down with them?  <br>(ooh, ooh....Analogy time!  Don't always buy the first tomato yo